Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
merge_hierarchical_def(25.10)                    merge_hierarchical_def(25.10)

Name
       merge_hierarchical_def  - Merges DEF data from various blocks to a sin-
       gle chip database

Syntax
       merge_hierarchical_def

       [-help]

       <defFiles <...>>

       [-add_blockage]

       [-delete_blockages_over_partition_macro]

       [-ignore_drcfill]

       [-incremental_ilm_def]

       [-preserve_shape]

       [-rdl_def <string>]

       [-rdl_orientation <orientation>]  [-rdl_placement {<x y>}]

       [-secondary {{<suffix> <def_file_list>}...}]

       [-skipNets]

       [-skip_filler]

       [-skip_pg]

       [-skip_routing {[pg|signal] [regular|special] [high_layer_routing]}]

       [-to_layer <routing_layer_name>]

       [-top_scope]

       [-topcell_orientation <orientation>]

       [-topcell_placement {x y}]

       [-transform_file <string>]

       [-use_top_def_die_area]

       [-modules <vCell>+ | -hInsts <hInst>+]

       Merges DEF data from various blocks to  a  single  chip  database.  The
       merge_hierarchical_def command provides the following features:

              * Takes the TOP DEF file and a set of block DEF files and merges
                them into a single chip database.

              *

                The  Verilog files for each of the blocks, and TOP, need to be
                loaded up front .

              * The block and TOP Verilog files (or their DEF  files)  can  be
                specified  in  any  order. However, if there are empty Verilog
                module stubs of blocks in some of the  parent  Verilog  files,
                ensure  that  the  parent Verilog files are specified prior to
                the child Verilog files.

              * There is no need to specify the LEF files for the blocks.

              * During the course of this command, TOP rows will be cut around
                the block boundary, and all block rows will be brought back as
                is.

              * Partition definitions are created for each  of  the  assembled
                block as per the DIE AREA statement in the block DEF.

              * The  wire  at  the  block boundaries will be stitched with the
                electrically connected net's wires at the TOP.

              * All orientations of blocks are  supported  for  assembly.  Re-
                peated  blocks  are also supported. Non-R0 master is also sup-
                ported.

Parameters
       -add_blockage
              Specifies that the netlist is a reduced one and converts the un-
              defined instances into blockages.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       <defFiles <...>>
              Specifies the DEF files to be merged.

              Data_type: list, required

       -delete_blockages_over_partition_macro
              Deletes the top design placement and routing blockages  overlap-
              ping partitions.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each merge_hierarchical_def parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man merge_hierarchical_def

       -hInsts <hInst>+
              Specifies the list of hierarchical instances for which  physical
              data  needs  to  be  loaded.  The  tool then reads data from def
              file(s) associated to the specified hInstance(s).

              Data_type: (hInst)+, optional

       -ignore_drcfill
              Ignores the special routing with DRCFILL shape attribute.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -incremental_ilm_def
              Incrementally flattens the ILM def.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -modules <vCell>+
              Specifies the list of modules for which physical data  needs  to
              be  loaded. The tool then reads data only from def file(s) asso-
              ciated to the specified module(s).

              Data_type: (vCell)+, optional

       -preserve_shape
              Preserve the shapes and geometries when the  DEF data from vari-
              ous blocks is merged to a single chip database.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -rdl_def <string>
              Specifies the RDL def file.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -rdl_orientation <orientation>
              Specifies the orientation for RDL def.

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -rdl_placement {<x y>}
              Specifies the offset of RDL def.

              Data_type: point, optional

       -secondary {{<suffix> <def_file_list>}...}
              Specifies the secondary DEF file(s) to load.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -skip_filler
              Skips merging the filler and decap cells.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -skip_pg
              Skips merging the routing on pg nets.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -skipNets
              Skips merging the signal nets section.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -skip_routing {[pg|signal] [regular|special] [high_layer_routing]}...
              Skips merging  the routing based on the settings specified. This
              setting can be any combination of the  three  optional  keywords
              from the following set:

              * [pg|signal]:  Specifies the type of the net on which the rout-
                ing to be skipped. pg - pg net, signal - signal net,  both  if
                not specified.

              * [regular|special]:   Specifies  the  type  of  routing  to  be
                skipped. regular - regular routing, special - special routing,
                both if not specified.

              *

                [high_layer_routing]: Specifies that only the routing on  high
                layers to be skipped, where the layers are calculated automat-
                ically.  If  not   specified,  the  routing  on all layers are
                skipped. The layers can be specified with -to_layer option. In
                that case, the routing on the layers from top to the specified
                layer are skipped.

                Note: You must specify the -to_layer parameter  explicitly  if
                high_layer_routing  is specified for -skip_routing. Otherwise,
                high_layer_routing has no effect.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -to_layer <routing_layer_name>
              Skips the routing of layers from top to the specified layer (in-
              clusive) when the high_layer_routing option is specified for the
              -skip_routing parameter.

              Data_type: (layer), optional

       -top_scope
              Merges the routing only on top scope nets.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -topcell_orientation <orientation>
              Specifies the orientation for the topcell.

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -topcell_placement {<x y>}
              Specifies the placement for the topcell.

              Data_type: point, optional

               -transform_file <string>" Specifies the name of  the  transform
              file that contains the final x and y offsets, orientation in the
              top-level  of  each  LEF block that got replaced by DEF, and the
              block's origin.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -use_top_def_die_area
              Enables the use of TOP DEF DIE AREA.

              Data_type: bool, optional

Example
              * The following command merges  DEF  data  from  top.def.gz  and
                blockA.def.gz to a single chip database.

                merge_hierarchical_def top.def.gz blockA.def.gz

Related Information
              * Partitioning the Design chapter in the Innovus User Guide

